PM-606 Final Report

About the Project

Project Background

For the summer 2022 semester PM-606 Health Data Science Practicum, we were tasked with utilizing a dataset from the California Teacher Study (CTS) with a focus on OSHPD hospitalization records. The dataset, particularly containing hospitalization information from participants between the years 2000 to 2015, had over 150 features related to participants baseline characteristics from questionnaires (age, race, family history, etc.) and their hospitalization information (procedures, length of stay, etc.). Using skills developed through core courses of the PHDS masters degree curriculum, we were expected to handle a large number of study participant records to make conclusions for four main aims.

Project Aims

The four main aims of the project were:

  1. Develop a best fitting model (either regression or machine learning) to predict the probability of death within a certain time window based on a plethora of participant features (patient-specific and hospitalization-specific)
  2. Assess whether the time window after hospitalization plays a role in predicting death
  3. Assess whether co-morbidities play a role in predicting the risk of death
  4. Determine whether there are temporal or spatial trends in hospitalization-related deaths


Abstract

Background: Using the CTS dataset, many prediction models of varying types were created for participants who passed away within thirty days after hospital discharge, as well as those who passed between the thirty-first day and sixth month mark. Focus was placed on discharge to death categories that were considered more recent to hospitalization, as too much elapsed time may introduce unreported changes in participant health history, behaviors, and other features (ex: passing away after three years may not be attributable to hospitalization compared to passing away within a week). Especially as recovery may produce many risks for death, tackling the first thirty day category is of the most interest and will likely bring more efficient models. Of the six discharge to death window categories created, the two that were used were the 0-30d and 31d-6mo categories.

Methods:

Data handling: First, data was extensively cleaned and wrangled for model-building, which included meticulously reviewing the provided data dictionary, removing duplicate instances, identifying clinically relevant features to prioritize, ensure consistency in variable types, handling missing values, creation of new variables, and conducting preliminary univariate and multivariate analysis through table creation and visualization. Such analyses helped to make a conclusion about the fourth aim concerning spatial and temporal trends in deaths. A subset of roughly 60 features was the final result after the processes previously described. Handling data took majority of the project time-wise, as evaluating an abundance of features on a one-by-one basis is a tedious task. Additionally, certain branding aesthetics, like using the same colors for visualization, were followed to make the report cohesive visually.

Model creation: After proper handling of data and implementing a data split of 70:30, models could be created with ease. Because the aim of the project was to create a binary classifier, there was a clearly-defined list of models to choose from. To implement a variety of methods, three main model types were pursued for the two target groups (first 30 days and 31d-6m): random forest models, logistic regression models, and extreme gradient boosting models. Feature selection for each model varied on some model restrictions revolving around the number of factors able to be handled, preference for parsimony, and highly correlated features. Because of the highly imbalanced classes (surviving participants heavily outweighing deceased), models were built with that in mind and the statistic used to compare models was balanced accuracy. Balanced accuracy was calculated by averaging the specificity and sensitivity from the model being run on the test set of data. AUC was ruled out as a staisticto compare performance because of the imbalance in the target variable classes.

Conclusions: After comparing balanced accuracy among the total of 6 models, it became evident that certain model types suited different participant categories more efficiently than others. With a balanced accuracy of 95.10%, the extreme gradient boosting model was most efficient for predicting participants death in the first thirty days post-discharge. On the other hand, with a lower balanced accuracy of 53.71%, the random forest model was most efficient for predicting participants death between the first thirty-one days and sixth month mark post-discharge. Regardless, many variables were identified as important across all model types, with patient disposition, cancers, major diagnosis codes, and health behaviors like diet and smoking most prominent in assisting model performance. Based on the difference in model performance for the different windows after discharge, it was evident that elapsed time post-discharge affects ones ability in predicting death. Furthermore, havgin certain co-morbidities, like specific cancer types, as well as the number of co-morbidities someone had, affected ones risk of death. Higher number of co-morbidities was associated with higher risk of death. Lastly, looking at the fourth aim of the project, lack of variance in seasonality across deaths demonstrated that temporal association for death was non-existent. Spatial differences were more difficult to discover without proper supplemental data, but inferences about death disproportionately affecting more rural areas lacking resources could be made.

The data set contains 48324 observations and 165 variables. These components denote that there are 48324 eligible participants for analysis and up to 165 available variables for each participant. The variables of this dataset primarily relate to birth and death dates, hospital admission and discharge dates, demographic characteristics (age, ethnicity, race), medical history (past diagnoses), health behaviors (sleep, diet, smoking), and metrics like height and weightamong many others.

Additionally, the number of missing values were counted across all variables in the dataset. Fortunately, the majority of missing values are attributable to a missing date for a procedure a participant never had, if questionnaires were not filled out by a participant entirely, if a participant never partook in a certain health behavior, or if a patient did not have a death date due to their current state of being alive. Furthermore, some missing values were also because only Yes was recorded in the dataset, meaning all other values were No, for example. These values, present with self-reported diagnosis variables, would be investigated further and handled in the next part of this report.

Ensuring Variable Consistency

After deciding which variables would be looked at initially, it was important to understand how variables could be made consistent in their values and types as seen in the data dictionaries. While many variables followed either a 0 and 1 binary value format, some follow an A and B or Y and N value format as well. It is crucial to keep in mind that A is equivalent to Y and 1 moving forward. That way, when reporting outputs and understanding models, there is no mix up. Furthermore, some binary variables technically included third options to indicate a participant not knowing their status, often denoted as Z.

Additionally, to make sure variables were following their intended variable type (num, char, date, etc.), column types for each variable were compared to data dictionaries. All variables of the type character were changed to factor variables for the sake of later imputation and usage in models, and integer or numeric variables were later changed to factor variables on a case-by-case basis (often those following a binary pattern).

Handling Missing Values and Outliers

For missing values, the only variables that could possibly undergo imputation were variables that have missing values on the basis of actually being missing. In other words, values for dates or choosing a random value for a participants diabetes status would be less acceptable. On the other hand, values that have more potential to be inferred, like sleep hours, based on the average or median sleep hour values would be more acceptable here. That would be done categorically, like imputing average sitting hours by gender. Before any handling, it was crucial to note that some values would be missing because such values were never available. For example, if a participant did not smoke or drink, there would naturally be missing values for smoking- and drinking-related variables for participants who never partook in such activities. For the sake of model-building and some models being unable to handle missing values, imputation was carried out by using mean values for integer and numeric variables and mode for factor variables.

To ensure there are no painfully obvious outliers, minimum and maximum values would be assessed for each variable used. The provided data dictionaries would be come helpful here once again, as ranges of values are listed in the dictionaries to ensure no values are too small or large upon comparison between the dataset in R and the dictionary. Code output is hidden to avoid extraneous length to report.

# Impute function to handle int, num, and factor at once
impute <- impute(data2, 
                 classes = list(
                   integer = imputeMean(),
                   numeric = imputeMean(),
                   factor = imputeMode()))

Even if missing values were kept in some regard, the percent of missing values are often below 5% for all investigated variables. This indicated that keeping missing values would not have impacted models too significantly (granted they couldhandle NA values). The only variables that may be of concern with the large number of missing values are those related to something like smoking, which near almost 35,000 missing values for each variable. However, such values are missing likely because of values not being applicable (ex: the participant is not a smoker and therefore does not engage with smoking). Many people evidently have not smoked, for example, which matches up well with the findings related to the large number of missing values for smoking-related variables. Imputation ended in there being 0 missing values in the dataset. Imputation was carried out by imputing mean values for integer and numeric variables, with mode values being imputed for categorical or factor variables.

All numerical values and their respective minimums and maximums were compared to provided value ranges in data dictionary. None were outside of expected boundaries. Additionally, no particular outliers were found in visualizations made in Tableau Reader, which was great to have to check in other way. With missing values handled and outliers checked, creating new variables came next.


Creation of New Variables

Once all variables were looked over to gauge completeness and consistency, creating new variables was the next step involved. From variables like birth date, admission date, discharge date, death date, diagnoses, and medications, many others could be created. The list of variables and their description are below:

  • Number of ICD Diagnoses:

    • Counts number of ICD diagnoses from the maximum five given

    • To see if number of diagnoses impacts risk of death significantly

  • Number of Comorbidities:

    • Counts number of comorbidities from the maximum four diagnosis CCS codes

    • To see if number of comorbidities impacts risk of death significantly

  • Number of Procedures Performed on Participant During Stay:

    • Counts number of procedures from the procedure variables in dataset

    • To see if number of procedures performed impacts risk of death significantly

  • Time to death

    • Looks at how many days from discharge it takes for a given participant to pass away

  • Time to death (categorical)

    • Looks at whether someone passed within the first month, between the second and sixth month, etc.

    • Will be helpful when sorting instances to use for models (ex: solely using 0-30 days, etc.)

  • Seasonality of death, admission, and discharge

    • To see if there are any interesting seasonal patterns in when most people are admitted, discharged, or pass away

    • Uses months to figure out season; not using solstices for ease of boundaries

  • Age at time of death

    • Uses birth and death date (where applicable) to get the age at which someone passed away

    • That way, if their age is extremely high, death may be attributable to age

    • Additionally, this gives more insight than age at baseline in relation to death

  • Number of medications taken

    • Counts how many medications a person takes daily (self-reported)

    • Used to investigate whether taking multiple medications makes for higher risk of death

From the plots above, some main univariate takeaways were:

  • Age at baseline is relatively normally distributed around the age of 60, while the age at death is visibly negatively skewed with most deaths occurring after about 80 years of age

  • Many participants die within the first year after being discharged from the hospital, as well as as far as 5 years after discharge

    • The relatively steady distribution across the discharge to death categories warrants model-building that specifically uses the categories in an isolated way

  • Majority of participants do not take daily medications

    • Whether or not they are prescribed to is not known (later variables such as a diabetes diagnosis, which often assumes a prescription of insulin, and whether or not insulin is taken daily) can create a variable related to adherence to medication at some point

  • A large percentage of participants experience the project maximum of 5 diagnoses

  • The participants in the study are generally not heavy alcohol drinkers

  • Many participants are sedentary (no strenuous/moderate exercise), while some receive a moderate amount of 1-5 hours a week

  • Most participants get a healthy 7-9 hours of rest a night, with some only getting 5-6 and a small amount sleeping even 3-4 hours a day/night

  • Most participants have never smoked before, with some having quit and a small proportion still smoking

  • Most participants belong to the SES category of 4, which denotes a high status

  • Most participants only stay in their respective hospitals for less than 5 days

  • The most common causes of death are Alzheimers, atherosclerotic heart disease, breast cancer, lung cancer, and stroke

  • Facilities were most often in Los Angeles, San Diego, Orange, Santa Clara, and Alameda counties

  • The majority of the population has Medicare as its payer, followed by private health insurance

  • Without any stratification of participants, there are no noticeable differences seasonally for death, admission, or discharge; most counts appear equal

Model Building

Carrying Out Data Splits

For model-building, the standard 70:30 training and testing split would be used. This would supply ample testing data for understanding model performance. The splitting of data resulted in data frames for both training and testing.

# Use splitTools to partition data
set.seed(33)
indeces <- partition(data6$deceased, p = c(train = 70, 
                                test = 30))

# Change target feature to factor
data6 <-
  data6 %>%
  mutate(death0to30 = factor(death0to30),
         death31to180 = factor(death31to180),
         death180to365 = factor(death180to365),
         death1to2 = factor(death1to2),
         death2to5 = factor(death2to5),
         death5up = factor(death0to30),
         deceased = factor(deceased))

# Training set
traindata <- data6[indeces$train, ]

# Validation set
testdata <- data6[indeces$test, ]


Random Forest Model(s)

Random forest models were tackled first, as the variable importance plot function was used to get ideas for which features to include in later model types. The more important a variable would be in the following models, the more inclined I would be to use it in a subsequent model type. A model was made for the 0-30d window and 31d-6mo window. From the subset of roughly 60 variables, competing target variables (ex: removing 31d-6mo binary variable when making a 0-30d death prediction model) and factor variables with too many levels were removed in order to run the model efficiently. To correct the imbalance of classes for the target variable, sample sizes were manually edited to reflect the count of the minority class in the training set. The mtry parameter was made to be the square root of the number of features used in the model. AUC and ROC plot outputs were made for each model despite an imbalanced target variable. Balanced accuracy was calculated for each variable.

### FOR DEATH 0 TO 30 DAYS AFTER DISCHARGE###
# Remove features with too many categories
traindata_rf <- traindata[, -c(10, 11, 46, 47, 48, 49, 50, 53, 56 ,
                               57, 58 ,59, 60, 61)]

# Figure out how many of minority class to balance model through sampsize

rf1 <- randomForest(death0to30 ~ ., data = traindata_rf,
                    mtry = sqrt(53),
                    ntree = 500,
                    strata = traindata_rf$death0to30,

                    sampsize = c(941,941))

For the Random Forest models, the specific discharge to death time frames used were 0-30 days (first month) for one model and 31-180 days (2 to 6 months) for another. Especially as time goes on, like when a participant is over five years out from a hospitalization, it may be harder to attribute death to their hospitalization. Hence, the discharge to death categories with windows closer to discharge were utilized. Using training and testing sets with a 70:30 split and a balanced Random Forest model, the following results came about:

  • For the model concerning the first thirty days after discharge

    • The AUC is particularly high with a value of over .90, which denotes commendable performance in distinguishing between classes.

    • Then, when contextualizing the AUC by viewing the ROC curve, it is evident that a trade-off exists between specificity and sensitivity. Therefore, different cutoffs for the model may assist its performance depending if deaths want to be truly predicted rather than survival and vice-versa. Because the model contains highly imbalanced data, it would be worthwhile to consider other metrics, since a high AUC may not tell a full story about the model performance here.

    • When instead using a confusion matrix to look at predictive performance for the model, a balanced accuracy metric that helps compensate for class imbalance demonstrates a roughly 50-60% accurate model on the test data.

    • With such a high sensitivity and low specificity, it is clear that having more instances for a certain class is advantageous for predictive performance. In this case, with so many participants surviving, the model sees more participants that remain alive and therefore is better at correctly predicting their survival. On the other hand, with less participants who pass away, there is less of an ability to distinguish deceased status because of fewer instances.

  • For the model concerning after the first thirty days up until the sixth month

    • The same patterns with the first model are seen, in which a high AUC falsely represents the model because of imbalanced classes for the many instances. A high sensitivity and low specificity here also demonstrate how imbalance can disrupt model performance.

    • Even with a far larger range of days (31-180) that participants can fall into, the predictive power when looking at balanced accuracy is slightly less than that of the other model, which deals with a shorter range after discharge. However, because the other model deals with participants who pass away closer to discharge, it is possible that it is more attributable to hospitalization and more related to the many features recorded closer to hospitalization chronologically.

  • It may be worthwhile in future renditions of this project to combine the two categories to chip away at the imbalance (ex: 0d to 6mo), since combining the two categories used in the model above will double the size of the minority class.

    • Expansion to having anyone who dies as far as the entire first year post-discharge may be helpful too

  • Many of the important variables in each of the models are similar. The ones with most overlap, which can help inform later model creation, between the two RF models created are:

    • Patient disposition codes

    • Cancer diagnoses

    • Age

    • Medication count

    • BMI

    • HBP

    • Diet

    • Major diagnosis code


Logistic Regression Model(s)

The main tool for binary classification learned throughout the PHDS program was logistic regression, and it is a formidable model type to try for this project. Building logistic regression models required more picky feature selection, as parsimonious models are often preferable and more interpretable. Especially with some factor variables nearing 24 levels, it was important to choose included features carefully to avoid overwhelmingly long output. Features were chosen with help of the variable importance plots from the random forest models, which helped initiate a preliminary model. Through forward selection and trial and error, AIC values of nested models would be compared. Ultimately, features were maintained if they were known to have significant clinical importance, were statistically significant in the output, or reduced AIC a sizable amount. For continuous variables, the fractional polynomial method was carried out to understand favorable transformations of those variables. Only one variable warranted a transformation, which was the count of procedures a participant had. The two logistic regression models actually had different independent variables included, as variables shifted in importance based on the window after discharge. For example, diagnoses were more important for the 0-30d model, while the model concerning death 31d-6mo benefited from inclusion of health behaviors like diet more. Balanced accuracy was calculated here as well.

Based on the logistic regression models created, there are clear differences in discharge to death windows and the ability to predict one versus the other. The 0-30d model made for a better balanced accuracy, and it demonstrated that many diagnoses can have adverse effects on risk of death. For example, endometrial cancer, colon cancer, diabetes, and melanoma are all risk factors for death, while having a lower BMI and being younger are protective factors for death. To quantify these risks, one can raise e to the value of the coefficient for a given variable (ex: having colon cancer makes someone e^1.14, or 3.126, times as likely to pass away in the first 30 days after discharge). While these models are harder to compare than others because of their varying independent variables, it was important to craft the models depending on the discharge to death window in order to have any potential predictive success.


Gradient Boosting

To round out the model-building in this report, gradient boosting was also carried out. XGBoost, or extreme gradient boosting, was the specific type used here. This model was able to include the most features compared to others and could handle factor variables with many levels. Again, competing target variables (ex: removing 31d-6mo binary variable when making a 0-30d death prediction model) were omitted from the model, as well as variables that may spoil a participants outcome (ex: including age at death or cause of death). To help balance the models, the scale_pos_weight was assigned the standard value of the number of the majority class divided by the minority class, which ended up being roughly 34 in both cases. Again, balanced accuracy was calculated here.

### FOR DEATH 0 to 30 DAYS AFTER DISCHARGE###
# Prepare data, removing features that may make death obvious
traindata_xgb1 <- traindata[, -c(10, 11, 12, 56,57, 58 ,59, 60, 61)]
x_train <- data.matrix(traindata_xgb1[, -52])
y_train <- traindata_xgb1[, 52]

testdata_xgb1 <- testdata[, -c(10, 11, 12, 56,57, 58 ,59, 60, 61)]
x_test <- data.matrix(testdata_xgb1[, -52])
y_test <- testdata_xgb1[, 52]


# Make into matrix
xgboost_train <- xgb.DMatrix(data = x_train, label = y_train)
xgboost_test <- xgb.DMatrix(data = x_test, label = y_test)

# Create model
watchlist <- list(train = xgboost_train, test = xgboost_test)
xgb_model <- xgb.train(data = xgboost_train,
                  max.depth = 3,
                  watchlist = watchlist,
                  nrounds = 100,
                  scale_pos_weight = 34,
                  verbose = 0)
xgb_final <- xgboost(data = xgboost_train,
                  max.depth = 3,
                  verbose = 0,
                  nrounds = 100,
                  scale_pos_weight = 34)

Aim #1 Conclusion: Best Models to Predict Death

Comparing Model Benefits

The three models utilized in this report are vastly different from one another and offer different benefits as a result. Logistic regression offers more quantitative reporting, with odds ratios derivable from coefficients holding other independent variables constant. On the other hand, the XGBoost model, though not quantitatively interpretable, offers greater predictive performance.

Comparing Model Test Statistics

For this particular report, the statistic used was balanced accuracy, as the AUC was not able to represent such an imbalanced dataset for the target variable. For the three models utilized (RF, LR, XGB), the balanced accuracies were as follows:

  • Random forest:

    • Model #1 (first 30 days after discharge): 58.13%

    • Model #2 (31 days to 6 months after discharge): 53.71%

  • Logistic regression:

    • Model #1 (first 30 days after discharge): 70.27%

    • Model #2 (31 days to 6 months after discharge): 50.39%

  • XGBoost:

    • Model #1 (first 30 days after discharge): 95.10%

    • Model #2 (31 days to 6 months after discharge): 47.86%

Based on the above statistics, the best model for predicting death among participants for the two discharge to death categories were:

  • First 30 days: XGBoost (95.10%)

  • 31 days to 6 months: Random Forest (53.71%)


Aim #2 Conclusion: Time Window Matters for Predicting

As seen throughout this report and from the conclusion for Aim #1, time window clearly makes a difference when predicting death. Between the two windows investigated (0-30d and 31d-6m), there were clear predictive performance differences that demonstrate that time windows after discharge affect models. As indicated in toward the beginning of this report, it logically makes more sense to have more accurate models closer to hospital discharge because variables are more accurate without as much elapsed time. Furthermore, the more time that passes post-discharge, the more room for other life events, health changes, and other participant variables to change. That way, death may become less associated with hospitalization and other recorded variables as time goes on. Also, seeing that variable importance shifts as different time windows are used with the same models, time windows are also different for the variables that are most associated with death.


Aim #3 Conclusion: Co-morbidities Matter

Certain co-morbidities impact the risk of death more or less than others. The most obvious diagnoses that impact risk of death were cancer-related diagnoses, as different cancer variables were repeatedly in important variable plots/lists for different models. For example, endometrial cancer being deemed more important than ovarian cancer for a model reveals that those with the former cancer may be better predicted than the latter. Looking at this aim more quantitatively, the logistic regression models demonstrate odds ratios of features as well. Based o the magnitude and sign of coefficients in the logistic regression models, there are clear differences in how some conditions affect risk of death. Exemplary of this is having colon cancer (1.14 coefficients), holding other variables constant, increases risk of death in the first 30 days after discharge more than having diabetes (0.273). Of course, having both conditions would more significantly impact ones susceptibility to death.


Aim #4 Conclusion: Spatial and Temporal Associations Lacking

Looking at plots produced earlier in the report during univariate and bivariate analyses, there were no evident differences in seasonality/temporality for death. The produced bar chart shows little to no differences in death counts for winter, fall, spring, and summer. Also, spatial associations are difficult to entirely comprehend without supplemental data like population size or deaths per county. A summary table was created earlier in the report to look at decease counts for each county, specifically looking at the 5 counties where death is most common. Naturally, death most often occurred in counties with more facilities/hospitals. The population density dilemma for figuring out spatial associations could be solved with data supplied from governmental sources or other trustworthy repositories. If any hypotheses were to be made for spatial associations, it may make most sense for deaths to disproportionately affect rural areas that have less resources and well-off health facilities.


Proposals

Upon investigating the four aims and getting to work with the data hands-on, I have some proposals I think are worth sharing.

  1. Including population-level data for each county, like deaths per county or number of women per county, would be interesting to do analyses like the spatial associations. This could help to standardize death rates and make them comparable across counties.
  2. Based on the variables indicated as important across the many models made, prioritize enforcing data managers or people who record data to ensure important variables are not missing. It could be helpful when predicting their risk of death to have complete data for variables that matter most!
  3. Focus on the important and impactful behavioral variables in models, for they are the ones that have potential to change rather than chronic diagnoses. If high carbohydrate diets are more impactful on people during their 31d to 6mo after discharge, implementing a program to inform people on nutrition importance would be beneficial.
